ce:section.ce:para:
In order to explore the catalytic effect of CDs and CDs/Fe2O3 on the thermal decomposition of TKX-50, a catalyst with a mass ratio of 1:10 was added to TKX-50. The DSC curves of different samples were obtained at heating rates of 5, 10, 15 and 20℃·min−1 (Fig. 7
                            and Table 1
                           ). Based on this, the thermal decomposition kinetic parameters of TKX-50 before and after adding catalyst were calculated under the different heating rate. In order to further compare the catalytic effect of the composite material relative to a single component, the decomposition catalysis of Fe2O3 on TKX-50 was also tested under the same conditions. It could be seen from the results that the thermal decomposition of TKX-50 mainly included two stages of continuous heat release: low temperature decomposition and heat release at 230∼250℃ and high temperature heat release at 250∼270℃, among which low temperature decomposition was the main heat release process [34,35]. With the amplifying of the heating rate, the decomposition temperature as a whole showed an increasing trend. At the heating rate of 10℃·min−1, the decomposition peak temperature of the two stages was 244.7℃ and 263.0℃, respectively. For ease of description, THDP is used to represent the high decomposition peak temperature and TLDP is used to represent the low decomposition peak temperature.

In order to explore the influence of catalyst on the thermal decomposition process of TKX-50 before and after addition, the mass spectrometry of pure TKX-50, TKX-50+CDs, TKX-50+Fe2O3, TKX-50+CDs/Fe2O3 was obtained by DSC-MS (Fig. 8
                           ). The comparison of molar percentage of TKX-50 thermal decomposition gas products before and after catalyst addition were obtained by integral calculation (Fig. 9
                           ). At high temperatures, TKX-50 was mainly decomposed into N2/CO (m/z = 28), CO2/N2O (m/z = 28), H2O (m/z = 18), NO (m/z = 30), NH3 (m/z = 17), HCN (m/z = 27) and NH2 (m/z = 16) [34–36]. The types of thermal decomposition gas products of TKX-50 after the addition of CDs, Fe2O3, CDs/Fe2O3 catalysts were unchanged, but the relative contents of different gaseous products changed significantly. According to the results, it was not difficult to see that the addition of CDs significantly reduced the content of the dominant gas product N2 from 37.6 % to 30.7 %, while HCN respectively increased from 1.2 % to 2.7 %. This might be due to the addition of CDs made the carbon content of the sample more abundant, which was more inclined to produce carbon-containing gaseous substances. When Fe2O3 and CDs/Fe2O3 were added, the content of H2O increased significantly (from 17.5 % to 27.9 % and 26.1 %), becoming the second largest gaseous substance after N2. The content of NH3 also increased (from 7.0 % to 8.1 % and 8.6 %). In contrast, the content of NH2 respectively decreased from 4.1 % to 1.8 % and 1.9 % and NO was from 8.4 % to 7.0 % and 7.1 %. At the same time, the content of CO2/N2O decreased from 24.2 % to 15.4 % and 16.3 %. This demonstrated that under the action of Fe2O3 and CDs/Fe2O3, unstable oxides and hydrides such as NH2, NO and N2O transformed into more stable gas small molecules such as NH3 and H2O.
